### SAMPLES

>Unknown sequence 1

>Unknown sequence 2

>Unknown sequence 3



### Stage 1

Open BLAST from NCBI: https://blast.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Blast.cgi
Enter FASTA sequence for mystery sequences 1-3.
Search Set: Nucleotide collection 
Program Selection: Highly similar sequences (megablast)
    Sequence 1: Feline coronavirus, 99.79%
    Sequence 2: Bacteroides fragilis, 96.86%
    Sequence 3: Escherichia coli, 100.00%

### Stage 2

Go to ORFfinder: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/orffinder/
Search entirety of each unkown sequence for open reference frames (nucleotides in between the start and stop codons)
Minimum ORF of 75bp
Genetic Code: Standard
ORF Start: ATG only
Ignore nested frames: True
Save longest ORF amino acid sequence as ORF_seq[unknown sequence #].fa
    Unkonwn sequence 1 - 3
    Unknown sequence 2 - 2
    Unknown sequence 3 - 1 


### Stage 3

Use ORF's from stage 2 to search for the name of the protein using blastp.
Use longest ORF from each sequence on the forward reading direction.
> blastp -db nr -query ORF_seq1.fa -remote | head -n 12

    Unknown sequence 1 - S [Feline coronavirus] [Feline coronavirus]
    Unknown sequence 2 - toxin RelE [Bacteroidaceae]
    Unknown sequence 3 - RNA polymerase sigma factor RpoS [Escherichia]

### Stage 4

Use blastx on the 3 new sequences (they are the same as the old sequences) to identify the proteins they code for.
> blastx -db nr -query sequence4.txt -remote

### Stage 5

Use web version of blastx on the feline coronavirus sequence.
Click the accession number
Pull up the nucleotide sequence of the feline coronavirus genome.
Download the genome and create a local database.
> makeblastdb -in feline_cov.txt -dbtype nucl

### Stage 6

Search database of feline coronavirus genome for the "unkown sequence 1"
> blastn -db feline_cov -query sequence1.txt -out feline_cov_s_protein.txt -outfmt 7
Check percent alignment and bit score.
